At Doniford, a remarkable result is the differing trends and, at some levels, the negatively correlations between the δ13Ccarb and δ13Corg
curves in the early Hettangian period (Fig. 3). The reproducibility of the shape of the δ13Corg curve has been reproduced from different sediments from around the world, confirming that these observed δ13Corg variations record global perturbations of the carbon cycle across the Tr–J boundary (McElwain et al., 1999; Pálfy et al., 2001; Ward et al., 2001; Hesselbo et al., 2002; Guex et al., 2004). The carbonate carbon isotope signal (™13Ccarb) across the Tr–J boundary has received less attention than the organic carbon isotope signal (™13Corg) and published data for this curve are limited to Austria, Hungary and Northern Italy (McRoberts et al., 1997; Pálfy et al., 2001;
Galli et al., 2005). The general shape of δ13Ccarb curves documented fromWestern Europe is very similar, despite the fact that the Doniford curve is offset towards lighter values. At Doniford, the absolute values of δ13Ccarb are influenced by local parameters such as depth, salinity, redox conditions and early diagenetic processes. This disparity between the δ13Ccarb and δ13Corg curves is not observed in recent studies where δ13Ccarb was measured using well-preserved oyster shells from others SW Britain sections (van de Schootbrugge et al., 2007; Korte et al., 2009). The Doniford δ13Ccarb curve from bulk sediment samples indicates a continuous record of alternating dysoxic and anoxic phases, with better carbonate preservation during anoxic phases. During these phases, pore water alkalinity may have been increased by bacterial sulphate reduction, thereby enhancing CaCO3 test preservation (Walter and Burton, 1990; Martin, 1999). Generally higher values of δ13Ccarb and δ18O in our dataset confirm that dissolution of carbonates was reduced during the anoxic phases (Fig. 3). As oysters could not develop in anoxic conditions, the oyster δ13Ccarb curve at Lavernock Point and at St Audrie's Bay in all likelihood records only phases of re-oxygenation. During these phases, dysoxic conditions occurred and, as light carbon was released in the environment due to the oxidation of organic matter, 12C was likely incorporated into the oyster shells during biomineralisation. Therefore, the δ13Ccarb signal from the oyster shellsmight have been strongly influenced by localised sea-bottom conditions. Vital effects have also likely occurred, as suggested by thewide intra-sample range of carbon isotope values reported by vande Schootbrugge et al. (2009) andKorte et al. (2009). At Doniford, the general patterns of δ13Ccarb and δ13Corg curves from the Blue Lias Formation, reflects a combination of local (sea-bottom conditions) and global (sea-surface recovery of primary productivity) signals. Thus, the relatively high values of δ13Ccarb at Doniford represent the primary palaeoenvironmental signal, while the short-termfluctuations of the δ13Ccarb curvewere drivenby local redox variations mainly controlled by early diagenetic processes. If the diagenetic impact was strong, all the δ13C values of carbonates would have shifted towards more negative values, but this is not observed.
